{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}
'''Hamad Aquatic Centre''' is a large [[swimming pool]] complex in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]]. As part of the Doha sports city that encompasses a number of other complexes in the area it was the venue for aquatic events at the [[2006 Asian Games]].

The Centre was the focus of controversy in October 2013.  That month, [[Israelis|Israeli]] swimmer [[Amit Ivry]] finished 2nd and won a [[silver medal]] in the women's 100 meter mixed individual medley at the [[FINA Swimming World Cup]] in swimming at the Centre, breaking the Israeli national record at 58.43 seconds.<ref name="ynetnews1">{{cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4443700,00.html |title=Qatar: Israeli record and silver medal to swimmer Amit Ivry |publisher=Ynetnews.com |date=October 21, 2013 |accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/22/israel-flag-qatar_n_4142292.html |title=Israel's Flag Makes Waves, Then Disappears at Swimming World Cup in Qatar |publisher=Huffington Post |date= October 22, 2013|accessdate=October 23, 2013 |first=Ron |last=Dicker}}</ref>  The Israeli flag was removed from outside the Centre at the FINA event, however.<ref name="jpost1">{{cite news|last=Sinai |first=Allon |url=http://www.jpost.com/Sports/Israels-flag-removed-from-swimming-event-in-Qatar-but-Israeli-swimmer-mounts-podium-anyway-329431 |title=Israel's flag removed from swimming event in Qatar but Israeli swimmer wins two medals anyway |publisher=The Jerusalem Post |date=October 22, 2013 |accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref> Furthermore, after [[Guy Barnea]] won a 200-meter butterfly heat, he posted a screenshot of a broadcast to [[Facebook]] in which the Israeli flag was displayed without the Star of David.<ref name="ynetnews1"/><ref name="jpost1"/> However, subsequent footage of the event released after Barnea's post revealed that the broadcast did not omit the Star of David.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/middle-east/1.630433|title=The Controversy That Wasn't: Qatar Displays Israeli Flag After All|publisher=Haaretz|author=Uri Talshir|date=7 December 2014|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref> The [[FINA]] [[Code of Ethics]] states that Fédération Internationale de Natation tournaments must have: “no discrimination on the basis of .. race, religion, or political opinion.”<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2013/10/22/news-opinion/israel-middle-east/israel-israeli-swimmers-face-discrimination-at-events-in-arab-countries |title=Israel, Israeli swimmers face discrimination at events in Arab countries |publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |date=October 22, 1923 |accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref>

The venue hosted the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2014 FINA World Swimming Championships]].

